{
  "title": "Benchmarking CLI Tools Using FastAPI in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This guide will demonstrate how to utilize FastAPI, a modern, fast (high-performance) web framework for building APIs, to benchmark command-line interface (CLI) tools written in Python 3.12+.",
  "key_points": [
    "FastAPI's ability to handle HTTP requests efficiently makes it an excellent choice for creating high-performance CLI interfaces.",
    "Using FastAPI's built-in performance metrics, we can easily measure the execution time of our CLI tools.",
    "We will learn how to create a FastAPI app that serves as a wrapper around our existing CLI tool, enabling us to benchmark it."
  ],
  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI\napp = FastAPI()\n\n@app.get('/{command}')\ndef {command}(args: str):\n    # Your command-line tool logic here\n    # Use subprocess or os to call your CLI tool\n    # Example: os.system(f'python3 your_cli_tool.py {args}')"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from fastapi import FastAPI, Depends\nfrom fastapi.responses import HTMLResponse\n\napp = FastAPI()\n\ndef get_perf_data(request: Request):\n    start_time = request.state.start_time\n    end_time = time.monotonic()\n    return {'duration': end_time - start_time}"
    }
  ],
  "version_notes": [
    "This guide focuses on Python 3.12+, but FastAPI also supports previous versions.",
    "Ensure you have installed the necessary dependencies using pip install fastapi[all] and uvicorn."
  ],
  "caveats": [
    "This approach requires modifying your existing CLI tool to work within a web context. This may not be feasible in all cases.",
    "While FastAPI provides efficient performance metrics, it's essential to understand that the overhead of running a web server should be considered when comparing results with traditional CLI tools."
  ]
